VGP marine kingdom is a large aquarium in Chennai. I was very impressed by the variety and quality of the exhibits. The aquarium is well-maintained and has a lot of information about the marine life on display.
The staff were friendly and helpful, and the tickets were reasonably priced at 695 per adult. Children below 100cm enter for free.
I especially enjoyed the shark tunnel, where you can see different species of sharks swimming above you. They had Great white shark and Guitar shark among other varieties on display.
They had an underwater flag display on account of Republic Day which was quite good. The also have a lot of touch displays which is a sure hit among the kids.
The aquarium also has a souvenir shop and a cafeteria, where you can buy snacks and drinks.
There is plenty of parking available at their lot.
I would recommend this place to anyone who loves aquatic animals and wants to learn more about them.

Embark on a thrilling adventure at the amusement park nestled in Chennai! My wife, children, and I visited around 10 in the morning. While the park was open, the rides didn't kick off until around 10:30, so we had a brief wait.

Once aboard the rides, we were treated to breathtaking views from the Ferris wheel and exhilarating moments on the roller coaster. The ride durations were relatively longer compared to those in Japan, offering ample time for enjoyment. Perhaps due to the early opening, we practically had no wait time for the attractions.

It was interesting to note Japanese characters on some of the park's rides, indicating they might have been imported from Japan as second-hand items. Despite their slightly aged appearance, the fun was unaffected. Plus, the entrance fee was reasonable, offering great value for money.

After experiencing the array of attractions by around 11:30, we noticed the park getting busier, prompting us to bid adieu. Highly recommended for families residing in Chennai, especially those with children!

text.text: We visited this temple in the month of February 2024. The Ashtalakshmi Kovil is a Hindu temple, which lies on the shorelines near the Elliot's beach, in Chennai, India. The temple is dedicated to the goddess Lakshmi, and her eight primary forms – the Ashtalakshmi – the giver of all eight forms of wealth, namely, offspring, success, prosperity, wealth, courage, bravery, food, and knowledge. The sanctorums are depicted on a multi-tier complex in such a way that visitors could visit all the shrines without stepping over any of the sanctorums. Try to visit this temple early morning in weekdays for skipping weekend crowds. If you are facing crowds then ask anyone for Special Darshan tickets which have separate lines and it’s movable fast.

I stumbled upon the Gunidy Snake Park by accident, as the adjacent Children's Park was closed for renovation. Surprisingly, it exceeded our expectations. The entry fees were reasonable, with kids at 10 rs, adults at 20 rs, and an additional 20 rs for carrying cameras or mobiles, while a separate camera incurred a 40 rs charge.

Inside, a variety of snakes, crocodiles, and turtles awaited. The park provided a satisfying experience for both kids and adults. Although some reptiles seemed motionless, leaving visitors questioning their authenticity, it added an intriguing touch. Turtles residing in a small pond were a delight for kids, despite the water needing cleaning.

The park offered small games, making it an enjoyable outing. However, the absence of restrooms is a drawback. The visit typically takes 1-2 hours, providing a quick yet entertaining experience. For reptile enthusiasts and those seeking educational value for kids, this place is a budget-friendly option.

As the Children's Park undergoes renovation, there's potential for the Snake Park to enhance its appeal by incorporating more reptiles and improving cleanliness. If these improvements are made, it could become a more engaging and educational destination for everyone. Overall, Gunidy Snack Park is a cost-effective and enjoyable option for a brief outing.
